This is a bug even if the customer is running into the situation described above.
If your create a user profile with the following call:
{code}
euare-useraddloginprofile --as-account test -u admin -p 'foo;bar'
{code}

A profile will be created with the password foo;bar

If you then try and log into the console using the password foo;bar you get the following error
{code}
2015-12-09 17:36:51 INFO http error {'msg': 'Bad Request', 'fp': None, 'code': 400, 'hdrs': None}
{code}
then the login page is reloaded without any error?

An incorrect password  will give you:
{code}
2015-12-09 17:32:27 INFO http error {'msg': 'Unauthorized', 'fp': None, 'code': 401, 'hdrs': None}
{code}
With the error 
{code}
Invalid user/account name and/or password.
{code}

[~dkavanagh], [~sjones]    How does this look?

AUTHORIZATION looks like:  username@account:password
CHANGEPASSWORD looks like:  username@account;password@newPassword

{code}
           // This ensures we at least have the pattern  '@' ';' '@' for change password.
            if ( (unEncodedAuth.lastIndexOf("@") > unEncodedAuth.indexOf("@") ) 
                  && (unEncodedAuth.indexOf( ";" ) > unEncodedAuth.indexOf("@") )
                  && (unEncodedAuth.indexOf( ";" ) < unEncodedAuth.lastIndexOf("@") ) )
            {
               isChangePassword = true;
            }
{code}

[~sjones] I think this should cover all cases. The first ':' or ";'  which would be right after the now un-encoded  "username@account" decides if it is a password change or not
{code}
            if ( !(unEncodedAuth.indexOf(":") < unEncodedAuth.indexOf(";")) ){
             isChangePassword = true;
            }
{code}
